    {
      "beat_id": "B02",
      "estimated_duration_s": 11,
      "narration_text": "Put the two predictions side by side. Bohr's angular-momentum rule gives E n equals minus 13.6 electron volts over n squared. Solving the Schrödinger equation for an ideal Coulomb atom gives exactly the same formula.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "compare"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B02.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 13.95,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B02.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T15:09:40"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B03",
      "estimated_duration_s": 8,
      "narration_text": "How can the energy be right when the orbit, trajectory, and definite radius are not the quantum state?",
      "shot": {
        "type": "CARD",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "hold"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B03.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 5.87,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B03.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T15:09:40"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B04",
      "estimated_duration_s": 11,
      "narration_text": "Bohr combines a circular Coulomb orbit with angular momentum quantized in units of h bar. That condition selects radii proportional to n squared and energies proportional to minus one over n squared.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "derive"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B04.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 12.89,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B04.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T15:09:40"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B05",
      "estimated_duration_s": 11,
      "narration_text": "Quantum mechanics instead solves for stationary wave functions. Their probability clouds can be spherical, lobed, or nodal. No electron travels around those shapes as a little planet.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "morph"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B05.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 10.92,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B05.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T15:09:40"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B06",
      "estimated_duration_s": 5,
      "narration_text": "The shared answer comes from the special Coulomb problem, not from a real orbit.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "CARD",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "hold"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B06.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 4.86,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B06.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T15:09:40"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B07",
      "estimated_duration_s": 12,
      "narration_text": "For a one-over-r potential, the quantum energy depends only on the principal number n, not separately on orbital angular momentum ell. That extra degeneracy reflects a hidden conserved structure beyond ordinary rotations.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "group"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B07.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 13.85,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B07.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T15:09:40"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B08",
      "estimated_duration_s": 11,
      "narration_text": "At n equals two, one 2s state and three 2p magnetic states all share minus 3.4 electron volts in the ideal nonrelativistic Coulomb theory, even though their wave functions look different.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "split"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B08.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 12.12,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B08.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T15:09:40"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B09",
      "estimated_duration_s": 10,
      "narration_text": "Bohr assigns that shell one circular orbit. The closest quantum analogue is the circular state with the largest allowed ell, not the entire collection of s and p states at the same energy.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "map"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B09.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 11.24,
